   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0763.xml"/>the Rev. Samuel
            Furly</persName></head>
         <opener><placeName>Cork</placeName><lb/><date when="1758-07-28">July 28, 1758</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>Dear Sammy,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p>Your conjecture is right. I never received the letter you speak of, nor heard before
            that you was in Holy Orders.<note place="foot" n="1">Cf. the previous letters from
                     <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> to <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0763.xml"/>Furly</persName> of <date when="1758-04-08"
                  >Apr. 8</date> and <date when="1758-05-03">May 3, 1758</date>. <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0763.xml"/>Furly</persName> was ordained deacon on <date
                  when="1758-05-21">May 21, 1758</date>.</note> I hope you are also in great earnest
            to save your own soul as well as those that hear you.</p>
         <p>You have need to pray much for steadiness of spirit and seriousness in conversation. If
            there be added to this the ornament of a meek and quiet spirit, your words will not fall
            to the ground.</p>
         <p>There will be danger, if you write so much, of writing in a dry and formal manner. We
            may suffer loss either by writing too little or too much. Observe every step you take.
            Walk circumspectly, and God will be with you. I am,</p>
         <closer><signed>Your affectionate brother,<lb/><persName>J.
            Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
         <postscript>
            <p>We expect to sail in three or four days.</p>
         </postscript>
      </body>
   </text>
